“…Maybe they didn’t like the narrative anymore. There are a lot of truths about Savitri. People just pick the one they prefer.”

But I knew the real one.
I was there.

“Maybe the whole idea of copy-pasting human beings was finally too messy for the birth of a world-saving God. So they didn’t try to impose it,” I said.

That’s when I saw it.

I knew that picture — just not that big. It covered half the wall.

Sixty people, arranged in rows. Old men with beards. Younger men. Women.

Some smiling — that particular Auroville smile.
Others more composed. Already somewhere else.

And in the front row — two children.

The younger one grinning, teeth bared, one missing.
The other one still. Calm, with a resolute stare.

The pride of the Tessier-Sen family.

Keshav and Valérian.

Anna.

“Oh, M01ra…” Nesh’s voice trembled inside me.

I cut the link to my vital immediately.

They had used children.

The fourth-generation Aurovillians had developed skills that interested these mad scientists. One of them was already a walking encyclopedia at four. Another could almost catch a bullet with their bare hands.

So why not add them to the mix?

Wisest minds. Kindest souls. Purest bodies.

Maybe because it’s sick.
Maybe because it’s dangerous.

Maybe because you don’t ask that of children who can’t make an informed choice. Children raised by families who believe too much in the Dream. Who yearn too much for it.

Yes, you do.

Because there was no reason to believe the process could lead to anything worse than, say, side effects such as psychosis or degeneration.

Just a benign procedure.

